1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,767
Every major bank, hedge fund, and now DeFi protocol needs to answer one

2
00:00:05,867 --> 00:00:10,891
question: how much could we lose in a really bad day? Value at

3
00:00:10,991 --> 00:00:16,511
Risk — VaR — is the industry's standard answer. It's a single number

4
00:00:16,611 --> 00:00:23,370
that regulators require, risk managers report, and traders live by. Today I'll show

5
00:00:23,470 --> 00:00:28,412
you three ways to calculate it and when each one lies to you.

6
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:37,058
Welcome to QuantiFire. VaR was popularized by JP Morgan's RiskMetrics in the

7
00:00:37,158 --> 00:00:44,312
1990s and became the global risk standard post-Basel II. It's defined simply:

8
00:00:44,412 --> 00:00:51,282
the maximum loss not exceeded with probability alpha over a given horizon.

9
00:00:51,382 --> 00:00:56,557
At 95% confidence over one day — 5% VaR — you're saying:

10
00:00:56,657 --> 00:01:02,492
on 95 out of 100 trading days, losses won't exceed this number.

11
00:01:07,066 --> 00:01:14,577
Method one: Historical Simulation. Take your portfolio's actual historical P and

12
00:01:14,677 --> 00:01:19,334
L series — say 500 days. Sort losses from worst to

13
00:01:19,434 --> 00:01:23,710
best. The 5% VaR is the loss at the 25th worst

14
00:01:23,810 --> 00:01:30,750
observation — that's 500 times 0.05. No distributional assumptions at all.

15
00:01:30,866 --> 00:01:36,024
The formula reads: VaR at confidence alpha equals the negative

16
00:01:36,124 --> 00:01:42,978
of the empirical alpha-quantile of historical returns. Pros: fully non-parametric,

17
00:01:43,078 --> 00:01:49,169
captures fat tails and actual market behavior. Cons: completely dependent

18
00:01:49,269 --> 00:01:54,088
on the historical window. If your window doesn't include a

19
00:01:54,188 --> 00:01:58,582
crisis, your VaR will chronically underestimate risk.

20
00:02:01,200 --> 00:02:08,630
Method two: Parametric Normal. Assume returns are normally distributed. VaR

21
00:02:08,730 --> 00:02:14,353
equals the negative of the mean minus z-alpha times sigma

22
00:02:14,453 --> 00:02:19,474
— where z equals 1.645 for 95% confidence. Scale to

23
00:02:19,574 --> 00:02:26,804
portfolio value by multiplying by total capital. Pros: fast, analytically

24
00:02:26,904 --> 00:02:30,620
tractable, easy to decompose by asset.

25
00:02:31,066 --> 00:02:38,873
Cons: financial returns have fat tails. The normal distribution massively underestimates

26
00:02:38,973 --> 00:02:44,444
tail losses. A 5-sigma event that should happen once every 3.5

27
00:02:44,544 --> 00:02:49,206
million days happens every few years in real markets.

28
00:02:51,866 --> 00:02:58,187
Method three: Parametric Student-t. Replace the normal with a t-distribution with

29
00:02:58,287 --> 00:03:02,467
estimated degrees of freedom nu. For nu around 4 to 6,

30
00:03:02,567 --> 00:03:07,302
you get realistic fat tails that match equity return data. As

31
00:03:07,402 --> 00:03:13,405
nu approaches infinity, you recover the normal. The gold t-distribution curve

32
00:03:13,505 --> 00:03:17,923
is heavier in the tails — that means higher VaR estimates

33
00:03:18,023 --> 00:03:23,155
that better reflect true market risk. This is strictly better than

34
00:03:23,255 --> 00:03:27,118
the normal method for any financial return series.

35
00:03:30,200 --> 00:03:36,710
VaR Scaling: the square-root-of-time rule. To convert a 1-day VaR to

36
00:03:36,810 --> 00:03:41,376
a T-day VaR, multiply by the square root of T. A

37
00:03:41,476 --> 00:03:46,625
5-day VaR is roughly 2.2 times the 1-day VaR. A 22-day

38
00:03:46,725 --> 00:03:51,292
monthly VaR is about 4.7 times the daily figure.

39
00:03:51,800 --> 00:03:55,701
Important caveat: this holds only if returns are

40
00:03:55,801 --> 00:04:01,786
independent and identically distributed. In practice, volatility clusters

41
00:04:01,886 --> 00:04:05,370
— bad days follow bad days. The square-root

42
00:04:05,470 --> 00:04:10,372
rule understates multi-day VaR during market stress periods.

43
00:04:14,066 --> 00:04:19,370
VaR's biggest limitation: it tells you the threshold, but says nothing

44
00:04:19,470 --> 00:04:24,157
about how bad losses can get beyond that threshold. Strategy A

45
00:04:24,257 --> 00:04:29,021
and Strategy B can have identical VaR numbers. Strategy A loses

46
00:04:29,121 --> 00:04:34,271
exactly the VaR amount when things go wrong. Strategy B occasionally

47
00:04:34,371 --> 00:04:38,363
loses ten times the VaR — there's a hidden tail spike

48
00:04:38,463 --> 00:04:44,230
the VaR number completely ignores. These are wildly different risk profiles.

49
00:04:46,800 --> 00:04:52,848
This is why Expected Shortfall — also called CVaR or Conditional VaR —

50
00:04:52,948 --> 00:04:59,963
was developed. CVaR equals the expected loss given that you have already breached

51
00:05:00,063 --> 00:05:05,146
VaR. It captures the full shape of the tail — the red zone.

52
00:05:05,246 --> 00:05:10,241
While VaR draws a line in the sand, CVaR asks: if we cross

53
00:05:10,341 --> 00:05:15,775
that line, how bad does it get on average? Basel Three and most

54
00:05:15,875 --> 00:05:21,836
modern risk frameworks now require CVaR to be reported alongside VaR.

55
00:05:25,200 --> 00:05:29,669
For DeFi: on-chain VaR needs two extra risk terms that

56
00:05:29,769 --> 00:05:35,253
no price series captures. First — liquidation cascade risk: during

57
00:05:35,353 --> 00:05:42,107
market stress, protocols become highly correlated and forced liquidations amplify

58
00:05:42,207 --> 00:05:47,861
losses systemically. Second — smart contract exploit risk: rare, but

59
00:05:47,961 --> 00:05:52,853
when it happens it can be catastrophic and instantaneous. A

60
00:05:52,953 --> 00:05:58,945
standard VaR model that ignores these will chronically underestimate the

61
00:05:59,045 --> 00:06:01,484
true risk of a DeFi portfolio.

62
00:06:03,200 --> 00:06:09,199
Key takeaways. One: always report VaR alongside CVaR — VaR alone says

63
00:06:09,299 --> 00:06:15,829
nothing about how severe losses can get once you've breached the threshold.

64
00:06:15,929 --> 00:06:21,576
Two: know your historical window and challenge it — if it doesn't

65
00:06:21,676 --> 00:06:27,764
include a crisis period, your VaR is optimistic. Three: if your return

66
00:06:27,864 --> 00:06:33,687
series has excess kurtosis above 3 — which is most financial assets

67
00:06:33,787 --> 00:06:40,052
— use Student-t, not Normal. Four: for DeFi, add liquidation cascade and

68
00:06:40,152 --> 00:06:45,268
smart contract exploit risk on top of any price-return VaR.

69
00:06:45,866 --> 00:06:50,577
Next episode: Factor Models — how quants decompose every

70
00:06:50,677 --> 00:06:56,161
return into systematic exposures, and why that changes everything

71
00:06:56,261 --> 00:07:00,886
about how you think about alpha. Subscribe. QuantiFire.

